  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Statement.}\n\nSynchronization between oscillators can be modelled by a phase‑locked loop equation.\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\n\nLet $\\theta(t)$ denote the phase difference between an input signal and a reference oscillator.  A first‑order phase‑locked loop (PLL) obeys\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\dot{\\theta}(t) = \\omega_{\\mathrm{in}} - \\omega_{\\mathrm{out}} - K\\sin\\theta(t),\n\\end{equation}\n\nwhere $K$ is the loop gain.  Locking occurs when the mean phase drift vanishes, i.e. $\\omega_{\\mathrm{in}} = \\omega_{\\mathrm{out}}$ and $\\sin\\theta(t)$ balances any mismatch.\nLinearizing around the locked state yields stability conditions on $K$.\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\n\nPhase‑locked loops are ubiquitous in signal processing.  Near the TZP they describe how energy and information streams adjust their phases to maintain coherence.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
